     "title": "Nominative & Objective Case (Singular); Perfect Tense",
     "summary": "A first reading where third-person singular perfect verbs tell a tiny story, and word endings (not word order) mark the subject and the object.",
     "lead": "Watch how the subject stays plain while the object picks up an -m ending (agnus becomes agnum).",
     "original": "Maria habuit parvum agnum. Agnus fuit albus. Maria venit in scholam. Agnus venit in scholam. Agnus venit cum Maria. Marcus vidit agnum in schola. Agnus dixit: baa, baa.",
     "explanation": "Here is an English sentence: Marcus saw the lamb (Marcus vidit agnum). There are three important words in it. **Marcus** is the subject, so it is in the **nominative case**. The verb is saw. The object is lamb, so it is in the **objective case**. Notice that the Latin verbs above all end in -it, and that the word lamb in English comes after the verb. In Latin we do not depend on the order of the words to show the object. We depend on the ending. Notice that many words above end in -m: that is the ending for the object. Some have -am, some have -um, some have -em. We need not worry about the various nominative endings today, nor about the special endings used after words like ad, cum, and in. Notice also that Marcus is just one person, so the subject is **nominative singular**. There is also only one lamb, which is **objective singular**. More than one would be plural. There is no Latin word for the and no word for a or an, so just supply these in English when you need them.",
